summary.seg: This manuscript, like many others included in the Curious Cures in Cambridge Libraries project, was once owned or used by Roger Marchall (c. 1417-1477) Rogerus Marshall (c. 1417-1477) , a doctor and physician to Edward IV. In common with numerous other manuscripts, Marchall added a table of contents to the beginning of the manuscript (p. [iii]) and added a title to one treatise in the volume 'Tegni Galieni cum comento Haly' on p. 251). Marchall's ownership or use of manuscripts is very well-attested, with forty-five surviving books (including this one) bearing evidence to connect him to them in some way; six others may have been his or accessed by him, and a further twelve are recorded but not traced.

As described by Linda Voigts, the present manuscript is one of eighteen (possibly nineteen) manuscripts at Gonville and Caius College that may be linked to Marchall, and which were probably donated by him to Gonville Hall (as Gonville and Caius then was); King's College and Peterhouse, where the study of medicine was also supported, received gifts of books from him too.

Thirteen manuscripts owned or used by Marchall (and another with possible Marchall connections) have been digitised, catalogued and conserved as part of the Curious Cures in Cambridge Libraries project:

binding.p: Rebound in 1909. Fully bound in leather over wood boards with matching blind-tooled decoration on both covers. Bound by J.P. Gray and sonJP Gray & Son, bookbinders, Cambridge, 1909: stamp on lower turn-in of the inside of the left cover.

Each cover is decorated with a double-fillet frame inset from the perimeter of the board by c. 10mm, and further divided into two unequal-width vertical panels by an additional double-fillet inset from the joints by c. 45mm. The left panel is decorated with four annulets, one set at each corner of the panel. The right panel is decorated with two fleurons, one set at the upper-, and the other at the lower-left corner of the panel.

Five raised bands on the spine. Spine compartments are decorated along their upper and lower perimeters with a single fillet. Head and tail bands with alternating red and cream segments. Two small printed paper labels affixed to spine '153' and '59' for the present shelfmark.
Paper pastedowns. Paper endleaves of the same paper stock at the pastedowns: pp. [a]-[d] at the opening of the volume and pp. [e]-[h] at the close of the volume - all blank.
Dimensions (l x w x d): 325 x 220 x 50 mm.

Previous binding described by M.R. James (1907) vol. 1, p. 51: 'Old binding, wooden boards, clasps gone. Chain-mark at middle top of front cover. The boards are lined with the most part of 4 leaves of an early xiith cent, (perhaps xith cent.) medical MS. in a fine small hand.'

The small bifolia (the '4 leaves' as described by M. R. James) that were used as parchment pastedowns in the previous binding were lifted during the 1909 rebinding and are now the parchment flyleaves pp. [i]-[ii] and pp. [vii]-[viii].

history.provenance: Owned by Roger MarchallRogerus Marshall (c. 1417-1477), fellow of Peterhouse, physician: the table of contents (p. [vi]) and a heading (p. 251) in his hand.
history.acquisition: Perhaps acquired from Roger MarchallRogerus Marshall (c. 1417-1477). At Gonville and Caius College by 1600, when it was recorded as no. 230 in the Ecloga Oxonio-Cantabrigiensis by Thomas James (1600).

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on Montague Rhodes James, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, 2 vols. (Cambridge, 1907-1908) vol. 1, pp. 51-52, and unpublished notes on this manuscript by Dr Debby Banham.

support.material: Two parchment bifolia, now flattened and mounted as two single sheets.

extent.seg: Two fragments: former pastedowns, now endleaves. These endleaves comprise two former bifolia, which were flattened and used as pastedowns in an earlier binding. When the manuscript was rebound in 1909 the pastedowns were lifted and mounted as endleaves, one at each end of the volume.
Two former pastedowns, now parchment endleaves pp. [i]-[ii] and [vii]-[viii] .

seg.note: Note that both the dimensions of the current flattened bifolium, and the estimated dimensions of a single leaf in relation to the fragment's original codicological context are given. There is pricking visible on pp. [i]-[ii], which permits a reasonable assessment of the original width of the leaf; the orignal height of the leaf has been reduced through trimming and rebinding and so is likely to have been greater in its original codicological context.

collation.p: Two former pastedowns lifted and mounted as endleaves, one at each end of the volume, pp. [i]-[ii] and [vii]-[viii].

signatures.p: No leaf signatures particular to this Part.
No quire signatures particular to this Part.

catchwords.seg: No catchwords particular to this Part.

supportDesc.condition: These leaves were used as pastedowns before being mounted as endleaves. Adhesive residue on pp. [i] and [viii]. Text on both leaves is faded and stained and difficult to read. Both leaves are stained and rubbed. Damage from the metal chain staple of an earlier binding present on pp. [i]-[ii].

layout.seg: Note that this part of the description refers to the dimensions of a single leaf when the fragment was in its original codicological context. Ruled in hardpoint, frame and lines. Ruled in single column format, 46 full lines visible and partial line visible along the upper (now inner) edge of the leaf.
Pricking visible in the outer margins.

handNote.p: Written in a late-11th or early-12th century protogothic with some caroline minuscule features. The script is of Anglo-Norman aspect. Main text written by one scribe, with corrections and marginal annotations in darker ink by the same scribe, or a second scribe with a very similar hand.

decoNote.p: No decorative features in this Part.

accMat.p: Parchment tab fixed to the centre of the outer margin of p. [ii]. The tab bears a character, perhaps the number '7' in ink, once large and in a darker ink, and once smaller and in very faint ink.

origin.origDate: Copied in the late 11th or early 12th century.
origin.origPlace: Written in England or perhaps northern France.

provenance.p: These fragments have been with volume since at least the later medieval period. The fragments were used as the pastedowns in the volume's former binding, a binding which included a chain-staple, which caused damage to pp. [i]-[ii]; the damage is visible along the upper edge of that leaf.

supportDesc.collation:
The quires in this Part are arranged as follows:
Parchment endleaves (bifolium; pp. [iii]-[vi]) +
Quire 112 (pp. 1-24)
Quire 214 (pp. 25-52)
Quire 32 (pp. 53-56)
Quires 4-78 (pp. 57-120)
Quire 86 (pp. 121-132)
Quires 9-138 (pp. 133-194, 197-214)
Quire 1412 (pp. 215-238)
Quire 156 (pp. 239-256)
Quires 16-2212 (pp. 257-418)
Quire 238 (pp. 419-434)
[iii]-[vi] + 112 214 32 4-78 86 9-138 1412 156 16-2212 238
Alpha-numeric leaf signatures (minuscule letter + minuscule Roman numeral) in ink in the lower outer corner of most rectos in the first half of each quire in this Part - some signatures lost to trimming. Some leaves are double-signed, and also have the Hindu-Arabic leaf signatures in the typical medieval forms in faint brown ink next to the alpha-numeric signatures ( e.g., p. 353 which has the medieval Hindu-Arabic '4' for the fourth leaf in the quire in faint ink next to 't iiii' indicating that this is the fourth leaf in quire 't').
Alphanumeric leaf signatures arranged as follows:
Quires 3-8 - 'b' - 'g'
Quires 11-21 - 'k' - 'u'
Quires 22-23 - 'x' - 'y'
No quire signatures particular to this Part. Catchwords present in the lower inner corner of the last verso of most quires in this Part, some framed in red ink.
supportDesc.condition: Leaves are in generally good condition, with only minor damage to text through liquid or friction damage or trimming. Large liquid stain on p. 104.

layout.seg: Written in two-column format, typically 42-48 lines to the page, and written below top line. Ruled in ink, frame and lines: six vertical single-fillet bounding lines (outermost line occasionally doubled) extending the full height of the page, and horizontal double-fillets extending the full width of the upper and lower margin of the page. Ruling occasionally added for marginal annotations. Pricking marks occasionally visible in the upper and lower margins.

handNote.p: Written in variable textualis by several scribes exhibiting a mixture of the typical 'northern' and 'southern' textualis features. Note that scribal change often coincides with quire division.

decoNote.p: Maniculae, and doodles with human heads around initials, e.g. pp. 79, 81, 86, 87, 90 etc.
Plain initials alternating red and blue throughout at the minor divisions of the texts.

note.p: Marginal annotations throughout in several contemporary and later hands.
